Introduction to Neural Networks: Bank Churn prediction¶

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

Businesses like banks which provide service have to worry about problem of 'Customer Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Objective¶

You as a Data scientist with the bank need to build a neural network based classifier that can determine whether a customer will leave the bank or not in the next 6 months.

Data Dictionary:¶

  • CustomerId: Unique ID which is assigned to each customer

  • Surname: Last name of the customer

  • CreditScore: It defines the credit history of the customer.

  • Geography: A customers location

  • Gender: It defines the Gender of the customer

  • Age: Age of the customer

  • Tenure: Number of years for which the customer has been with the bank

  • NumOfProducts: refers to the number of products that a customer has purchased through the bank.

  • Balance: Account balance

  • HasCrCard: It is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer has credit card or not.

  • EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary

  • isActiveMember: Is is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer is active member of the bank or not ( Active member in the sense, using bank products regularly, making transactions etc )

  • Exited : whether or not the customer left the bank within six month. It can take two values 0=No ( Customer did not leave the bank ) 1=Yes ( Customer left the bank )

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

First thing I want to know is about the target variable. Is it imbalanced?

In [9]:
data['Exited'].value_counts()
Out[9]:
0    7963
1    2037
Name: Exited, dtype: int64

It does appear imbalanced with the majority of rows being non-exiting customers. This tells me a few things:

  • A model that predicts "zero only" will be about 80% accurate. That is the low bar for performance. Any model will have to have better than 80% accuracy to be an improvement.
  • We should use Recall as our prioritized performance metric since we want to optimize the number of exits we catch.
  • It might be helpful to rebalance our training data with techniques such as SMOTE.

Data Preprocessing¶

  • Missing value treatment
  • Feature engineering (if needed)
  • Outlier detection and treatment (if needed)
  • Preparing data for modeling
  • Any other preprocessing steps (if needed)

RowNumber, CustomerID, and Surname should have no relevance to the target variable, so these will all be removed from the training data.

Furthermore, we can one-hot encode the categorical features, Gender and Geography.

Finally, we will split the data into train and test datasets and scale the numerical variables separately.

In [14]:
#Drop meaningless features
df = data.drop("RowNumber", axis=1
).drop("CustomerId", axis=1
).drop("Surname", axis=1)

#One-hot encode categorical variables
df = df.join(pd.get_dummies(df['Gender'])
).join(pd.get_dummies(df['Geography'])
).drop("Gender", axis=1
).drop("Geography", axis=1
)

#Split target variable from rest of dataset
features = df.drop("Exited", axis=1)
target = df['Exited']

#Split dataset into training and testing sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test =  train_test_split(features, target, test_size=0.25, random_state=1)

#Scale datasets to work with normalized numbers
scaler = MinMaxScaler()
X_train = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test = scaler.fit_transform(X_test)

y_train = np.array(y_train)
y_test = np.array(y_test)

Model Building¶

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

Sometimes you really want to focus on recall, precision, or overall accuracy, depending on the business implications of type I or type II errors. In this case, what would the bank do if they detect a customer might exit? Offer some deal to keep them? That has costs.

I believe the best application of this model will be to project the correct number of customers the bank will have some time in the future. Knowing that they'll keep, let's say, 80% of their customers will allow them to create accurage budgets and plans even in the future. They have to be aware if that number can change, though. Say in a certain quarter that the model says that 30% of their customers are predicted to leave within six months. That may allow them to adjust their future budget downward and avoid being caught by surprise.

Because we care about the number of total customers that both stay and exit, we will prioritize accuracy as our optimized metric.

Model Building: Neural Network¶

Let's begin with a simple network with no fancy flairs: just 2 hidden layers and an output layer.

In [15]:
#Create a model with two hidden layers and one output node

model_nn.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
model_nn.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')) #sigmoid is best for binary classification

plt.plot(history_1.history['accuracy'])

This is an obvious example of an overfit as the training accuracy went up but the validation wasn't affected at all as the model kept tuning. We end up with 96% accuraccy in the training set but only 79% in the validation set, not even better than our bare minimum benchmark. We may need to reduce the complexity of the model. One way is with Dropout.

Model Improvement: Neural Network model with Dropout¶

In [24]:
#Add dropout to each hidden layer
model_drop = Sequential()
model_drop.add(Dense(64, activation='relu', input_shape=(X_test.shape[1],)))
model_drop.add(Dropout(0.5))
model_drop.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
model_drop.add(Dropout(0.5))
model_drop.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

model_drop.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics = ['accuracy'])
model_drop.summary()

Model Improvement: Neural Network model with Hyperparameter tuning¶

In [27]:
def buildModel(optimizer, hidden_layers, hidden_layer_size, dropout): 
    model = Sequential()
    
    for i in range(hidden_layers):
        model.add(Dense(hidden_layer_size, activation='relu'))
        model.add(Dropout(dropout))
    
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=optimizer, metrics=['accuracy'])
    
    return model
In [28]:

Model Comparison¶

Final Model¶

In [80]:
y_pred = np.round(best.predict(X_test))
#Output is a probability, so rounding sets it to whichever is closer, 0 or 1.

print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred):>.2%}")
print(f"Recall: {recall_score(y_test, y_pred):>.2%}")
print(f"Precision: {precision_score(y_test, y_pred):>.2%}")
print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))

Accuracy: 79.88%
Recall: 51.15%
Precision: 51.65%
[[1731  249]
 [ 254  266]]

I have to say this was a little disappointing. Our best-performing model (Adam optimizer, 3 hidden layers of 64 nodes, and no dropout) still only reached 80% accuracy.

It is perhaps better than the "no exiters" model, despite the same accuracy. The model was fairly balanced between recall and precision, where recall is the percent of positive cases we detected and precision is the rate that a predicted positive was correct. So theoretically these values would adjust even if we have an unusually large or small number of exiters in a six-month period. The "no exiters" model would predict a static 20% loss even in those cases.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

What recommedations would you suggest to the bank?

  • The model is not yet good enough to be able to suggest actions for individual customers, such as marketing or promotion efforts to retain potential exiters.

  • The model might be good enough to help predict overall churn, which could be used to set budgets six months from now.

  • The drawback of a neural net vs. other models is that feature importance or correlation coefficients are hidden inside the inner workings of the model. More advanced techniques would be required to determine how much each of the features are actually mattering for calculating the predictions. This data might be helpful to t he bank for developing policies on dealing with customers of different genders or geography.
